          </div>
          <div class="contact">
            <strong>Jordan Taylor</strong>
            <p>Contact information available upon request</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="lender-card">
        <h3>American Financing</h3>
        <div class="lender-contacts">
          <div class="contact">
            <strong>Phillip King</strong>
            <p>Contact information available upon request</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="lender-card">
        <h3>Union Home Mortgage</h3>
        <div class="lender-contacts">
          <div class="contact">
            <strong>John Reid</strong>
            <p>Contact information available upon request</p>
          </div>
          <div class="contact">
            <strong>Tammy Reid</strong>
            <p>Contact information available upon request</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="lender-note">Each of these lenders understands the construction-to-permanent loan process, has worked with CORELOT builds before, and communicates clearly throughout the draw process.</p>
    <p class="recommendation"><strong>We recommend contacting 2-3 lenders to compare rates, fees, and terms.</strong> They'll compete for your business, and you'll have confidence you're getting the best fit for your situation.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section faq-section">
    <h2>Common Questions</h2>

    <div class="faq-grid">
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h4>Why start with a design retainer instead of just getting pre-approved?</h4>
        <p>Because pre-approval doesn't mean much without accurate numbers. If you get pre-approved for $400,000 but your actual project costs $475,000 due to site work, you've wasted time. The design retainer ensures you know real costs before involving lenders.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h4>Can I finance both land purchase and construction?</h4>
        <p>Yes. Construction-perm loans can include land acquisition if you don't already own the lot. The land purchase happens at closing, then construction begins.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h4>What if my lot needs significant site work?</h4>
        <p>That's exactly what the design retainer uncovers. We'll get real estimates for clearing, grading, utilities, and access before you commit to anything. Site work is the variableâ€”plans are priced.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h4>What if I want to make plan modifications?</h4>
        <p>That's handled during the design retainer phase. Any plan updates are priced upfront and included in your budget before you approach lenders. No surprises.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h4>Do I need construction experience to qualify?</h4>
        <p>No. Lenders work with first-time builders regularly. Having an experienced licensed builder (CORELOT) and detailed plans actually strengthens your application.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <h4>How long does construction take?</h4>
        <p>Most CORELOT builds finish in 8-12 months from groundbreaking, depending on plan size and site conditions. Weather, permit timing, and material availability can affect schedules.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="cta-section">
    <div class="cta-box">
      <h2>Ready to start with a design retainer?</h2>
      <p>The first step is understanding your true project cost. Schedule a consultation to review your lot conditions, discuss site work variables, and build a detailed project budget.</p>
      <div class="cta-contacts">
